{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632277"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:39:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:39:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17430"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17430"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70778"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5339"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23799"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70778"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETemperature measurements consistently show that urban areas are warmer than surrounding rural regions, even when controlling for other environmental factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary cause of higher temperatures in urban areas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heat absorption and retention by built structures","Higher concentration of greenhouse gases","Increased wind speeds between buildings","Greater human population density","Higher altitude of city centres"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe urban heat island effect is primarily caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Eheat absorption and retention by built structures\u003C/strong\u003E. Dark surfaces like asphalt and concrete absorb and store more solar radiation than natural surfaces, releasing it slowly as heat. Additionally, the reduction in vegetation reduces cooling through evapotranspiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher concentration of greenhouse gases\u003C/strong\u003E - While urban areas have higher local emissions, these gases have minimal impact on local temperature compared to structural effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased wind speeds between buildings\u003C/strong\u003E - Building arrangements typically create wind barriers and reduce airflow rather than increase it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreater human population density\u003C/strong\u003E - Although human activity generates some heat through metabolism and energy use, this contribution is minimal compared to structural heat retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher altitude of city centres\u003C/strong\u003E - Higher altitudes generally result in cooler temperatures due to atmospheric effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe temperature difference between urban and rural areas is most pronounced at night when stored heat is released from built structures. This effect can be mitigated through urban planning strategies like increasing green spaces and using reflective building materials.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The urban heat island effect causes cities to be warmer than surrounding rural areas due to heat absorption and retention by built structures.","Dark surfaces like asphalt and concrete absorb more solar radiation than natural surfaces.","Reduced vegetation in urban areas decreases cooling through evapotranspiration."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Heaviside C, Macintyre H, Vardoulakis S. The Urban Heat Island: Implications for Health in a Changing Environment. Curr Environ Health Rep. 2017;4(3):296-305. doi:10.1007/s40572-017-0150-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17430"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:58:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:59:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10120"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70778"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":nu